    <router-outlet _ngcontent-serverapp-c4193883768=3D""></router-outlet><a=
pp-levene-test><h1 id=3D"Levene-Test" class=3D"mb-4">Levene Test</h1>

<p>
  Many statistical testing procedures require that there is
  <b>equal variance</b> in the samples. How can it now be checked whether t=
he variances
  are homogeneous, i.e. whether there is equality of variance? This is wher=
e the
  <b>Levene test</b> helps. The Levene test checks whether several groups h=
ave the same
  variance in the population.
</p>
<app-video-frame _nghost-serverapp-c2585983582=3D""><div _ngcontent-servera=
pp-c2585983582=3D"" class=3D"videoFrame mb-3 mt-4 ml-0">
  <iframe _ngcontent-serverapp-c2585983582=3D"" title=3D"YouTube video" loa=
ding=3D"lazy" allow=3D"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope;=
 picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=3D"" src=3D"cid:frame-5D8ECC9ACB928731=
55335AA4BE3CDCDC@mhtml.blink"></iframe>
</div><!---->
</app-video-frame>

<p>
  Levene's test is therefore used to test the null hypothesis that the samp=
les to be
  compared come from a population with the same variance. In this case, pos=
sible variance
  differences occur only by chance, since there are small differences in ea=
ch sampling.
</p>
<img alt=3D"Levene-Test" title=3D"Levene-Test" src=3D"https://numiqo.com/as=
sets/tutorial/levene_test_en.png">
<p>
  If the p-value for the Levene test is greater than .05, then the variance=
s are not
  significantly different from each other (i.e., the homogeneity assumption=
 of the
  variance is met). If the p-value for the Levene's test is less than .05, =
then there is a
  significant difference between the variances.
</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>H<sub>0</sub>:</b> Groups have equal variances</li>
  <li><b>H<sub>1</sub>:</b> Groups have different variances</li>
</ul>

<p>
  It is important to note that the mean values of the individual groups hav=
e no influence
  on the result, they may differ. A big advantage of Levene's test is that =
it is very
  stable against violations of the normal distribution. Therefore, Levene's=
 test is used
  in many statistics programs.
</p>

<p>
  Furthermore, the variance equality can also be checked graphically, this =
is usually done
  with a grouped
  <a routerlink=3D"/statistics-calculator/charts/create-boxplot" href=3D"ht=
tps://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/charts/create-boxplot">box-plot</a> =
or with a
  <a routerlink=3D"/statistics-calculator/charts/create-scatterplot" href=
=3D"https://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/charts/create-scatterplot">Sca=
tterplot</a>.
</p>

<h2>Assumptions for the Levene test</h2>

<p>Der Levene-Test hat grunds=C3=A4tzlich zwei Voraussetzungen:</p>

<ul>
  <li>independent observations</li>
  <li>
    the test variable has
    <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/level-of-measurement" href=3D"https://numiqo=
.com/tutorial/level-of-measurement">metric scale level</a>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"Levene-Test-Example">Levene Test Example</h2>

<p>
  In this fictitious example, you conducted a survey among students to find=
 out how many
  cups of coffee they drink per week. Now you want to know whether the vari=
ances of the
  individual subjects are the same and calculate a levene test for this.
</p>

<table class=3D"table table-sm table-nonfluid">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Math</th>
      <th>History</th>
      <th>Psychology</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>21</td>
      <td>18</td>
      <td>17</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>23</td>
      <td>22</td>
      <td>16</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>17</td>
      <td>19</td>
      <td>23</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>11</td>
      <td>26</td>
      <td>7</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>9</td>
      <td>13</td>
      <td>26</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>27</td>
      <td>24</td>
      <td>9</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>22</td>
      <td>23</td>
      <td>25</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>12</td>
      <td>17</td>
      <td>21</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>20</td>
      <td>21</td>
      <td>14</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>4</td>
      <td>15</td>
      <td>20</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>
  To calculate the Levene test, simply copy the upper table into the table =
in the
  Statistics Calculator and then click on
  <a routerlink=3D"/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test" href=3D"https://=
numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test">Hypothesis tests</a>. Now=
 you
  just need to select the three variables Math, History and Psychology and =
an ANOVA will
  be calculated. Here you will now also find a calculated Levene test.
</p>
<p>
  As a result you get two tables and a box plot. The first table describes =
the variables
  descriptive and you can read the standard deviation of each variable.
</p>

<img alt=3D"Levene-Test Variance" title=3D"Levene-Test Variance" src=3D"htt=
ps://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/levene_test_variance.png">
<p>
  With the help of the boxplot you can visualize the result of the Levene t=
est. The
  boxplot shows clearly how much the examined variables scatter.
</p>

<img alt=3D"Levene-Test Boxplot" title=3D"Levene-Test Boxplot" src=3D"https=
://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Levene-Test-Boxplot_en.png">

<p>
  After the boxplot you will now get the table with the Levene test statist=
ics. In this
  table the significance is the most important value, if the significance i=
s above 0.05
  there is no difference between the variances of the samples.
</p>

<img alt=3D"Levene-Test Example" title=3D"Levene-Test Example" src=3D"https=
://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/levene_test_example.png">

<p>
  Therefore you can easily calculate a levene's test for equality of varian=
ces. If the
  p-value or significance is less than 0.05, you can assume inhomogeneous v=
ariance based
  on the available data.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"Interpreting-Levene-Test">Interpreting the Levene Test</h2>

<p>
  The <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/degrees-of-freedom" href=3D"https://numiqo=
.com/tutorial/degrees-of-freedom">degree of freedom</a> df1 is obtained
  by calculating the number of groups minus 1, the degree of freedom df2 is=
 obtained by
  calculating the number of cases minus the number of groups. In this level=
-test example
  the significance of 0.153 is greater than the defined significance level =
of 5%.
</p>

<img alt=3D"Interpreting-Levene-Test" title=3D"Interpreting-Levene-Test" sr=
c=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Levene_Test_Interpretation.png">

<p>
  Thus the null hypothesis is maintained and there is no difference between=
 the variances
  of the three groups. Thus, the three samples come from populations with t=
he same
  variance.
</p>
</app-levene-test><!---->

